iment of Horse, Connecticut Line (Capt. Curtis, Lt. Judson, Ensign Martin)","notes":"Per his August 15, 1832 pension application: enlisted last day of April 1775; served in Col. Sheldon's regiment of horse, Connecticut Line, under Major Bull, Capt. Agin (?) Curtis, Lieutenant Judson, and Ensign Martin; discharged November 1, 1777 at Fairfield CT. Pension application rejected for lack of proof (no service record found in Connecticut, and David at age 80 in 1833 had been unable to produce witnesses). Pension File R.7633, Conn., Newton, David. Service was the basis for his 1777 winter migration to Hartford VT."},{"war":"American Revolutionary War","war_id":"WAR004","rank":"Private","rank_start":"Private","rank_end":"Private","rank_year_start":1780,"rank_year_end":1780,"unit":"Capt. Joshua Hazen's Hartford Co., Vermont Militia","notes":"Royalton Alarm, October 1780 (Vermont militia response to the Tory-and-Indian raid on Royalton VT). NSSAR membership #117807. Documented in John E. Goodrich, Rolls of Soldiers in the Revolutionary War, 1904, pp. 283-284. This Vermont militia service post-dates his Connecticut Line service (1775-1777) and reflects his 1777 migration to Hartford VT."}],"bio":{"display_name":"David Newton","first_name":"David","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[]},"residence":{"city":"Hartford","county":"Windsor","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"migration","header":"Crossed to Vermont on the frozen Connecticut River","body":"David Newton moved his family from Connecticut to Hartford Vermont in 1777, traveling in the dead of winter and using the ice-covered Connecticut River as a highway according to family tradition. Just before his marriage four years earlier he had bought twenty-five acres of the Hazen home lot in Woodbury Connecticut."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Family record called most remarkable in the country","body":"A Newton family historian called this household's record 'the most remarkable one known in the United States, if not in the world, in respect to the number of children, their individual length of life, and the aggregate of the ages of the whole family.' David and Mary raised at least nine documented children in Hartford Vermont; David lived to eighty-six."}],"slug":"david-newton-1753"},"I00101":{"id":"I00101","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_thomas_spouse":true,"is_talcott_spouse":false},"birth":{"year":1754,"month":9,"day":11,"city":"Norwich","state":"Connecticut","county":"New London","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1823,"month":2,"day":4,"country":"United States"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"HD0233","children_ids":["HD0238","HD0239","HD0240","HD0241","HD0242","HD0243","HD0244","HD0245","HD0246"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1773,"date_month":9,"date_day":16,"end_type":"death","end_year":1823}],"sources":[],"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Mary Hazen Newton","first_name":"Mary","last_name":"Newton","maiden_name":"Hazen","married_names":["Newton"],"gender":"female"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"migration","header":"Crossed to Vermont on a frozen river","body":"Mary married David Newton in Woodbury Connecticut in September 1773. Four years later in the dead of winter the family used the ice-covered Connecticut River as a highway